@NoquarterWnv But the idea that public libraries are somehow different is ludicrous. They serve specific populations, their communities. Demographics are a huge part of collection building and programming. Always have been.

@NoquarterWnv Yes. Outside of the public libraries, LAM (libraries, archives, museums) institutions have always served specific populations and functions and are categorized accordingly as academic or special libraries (e.g. government, corporate, law, music, etc.)
I've never met a librarian who was unwilling to help a patron who wanted information on topics that were at odds with the librarian's social or political beliefs.

Collection development is driven by users. Libraries are collecting more diverse collections because the communities they serve are asking for them. We're there to provide the information that people want. Neutrality comes in when people with whom we disagree request stuff.

It's a direct response to the drastic change in the information landscape over the last several decades. Libraries can no longer be "all things for all people." We can't collect it all. To succeed and survive, libraries have had to adapt to providing users with what they want.
I think it's important to highlight in any conversation about neutrality in libraries that it can't be boiled down to simply an ideological shift pushed by a cadre of "woke librarians"
